const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do electrolyte gummies work as well as electrolyte drinks?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Electrolyte gummies deliver the same minerals (sodium, potassium, magnesium) as electrolyte drinks, but they lack the immediate hydration benefit of water that drinks provide. For optimal hydration during exercise, pair electrolyte gummies with water. Gummies are particularly convenient for activities where carrying mixed drinks is impractical — running, hiking, cycling, or travel. Absorption of the electrolyte minerals themselves is comparable between formats when adequate water is consumed alongside the gummies.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How many electrolytes do I lose during exercise?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The primary electrolyte lost through sweat is sodium — approximately 500-1,500mg per liter of sweat, depending on individual sweat rate, genetics, and acclimatization. Potassium losses are approximately 100-200mg per liter. Magnesium and calcium losses are smaller (10-30mg per liter). A moderate one-hour workout producing 1 liter of sweat depletes approximately 800mg sodium and 150mg potassium. Endurance athletes training in heat for 2+ hours can lose 2,000-4,000mg sodium, requiring aggressive electrolyte replacement during and after exercise.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'When should I take electrolyte gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Before exercise: 30-60 minutes before to pre-load electrolytes, particularly before endurance or hot-weather training. During exercise: every 30-45 minutes during sessions lasting longer than 60 minutes, consumed with water. After exercise: within 30 minutes post-workout to replace losses and support recovery. For daily use: morning or afternoon to address general electrolyte needs from diet, medication (diuretics), or climate-related dehydration. Always consume adequate water alongside electrolyte gummies.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What are the signs of electrolyte imbalance?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Early signs include muscle cramps, fatigue, headache, dizziness, dark urine, and difficulty concentrating. Moderate depletion causes nausea, irregular heartbeat, numbness or tingling, and significant weakness. Severe electrolyte imbalance (hyponatremia or hypernatremia) can cause confusion, seizures, and requires medical attention. Athletes should monitor urine color (pale yellow indicates adequate hydration), weigh themselves before and after exercise (each pound lost equals ~16oz of fluid deficit), and note any cramping patterns that suggest specific mineral depletion.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How much sodium do I need during exercise?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The American College of Sports Medicine recommends 300-600mg of sodium per hour of exercise lasting longer than 60 minutes. Salty sweaters (white residue on clothing), endurance athletes, and those training in heat may need 600-1,000mg per hour. Most electrolyte gummies provide 100-300mg sodium per serving, so 1-3 servings per hour of intense exercise covers most athletes. Individualize your sodium intake by monitoring cramping patterns, sweat rate, and salt residue on skin and clothing.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Are electrolyte gummies keto-friendly?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Electrolyte supplementation is particularly important on ketogenic diets because the low-insulin state increases sodium and potassium excretion through the kidneys. This "keto flu" — headaches, fatigue, cramps — is largely caused by electrolyte depletion. Most electrolyte gummies contain 2-4g sugar per serving, which is negligible for keto compliance. Sugar-free electrolyte gummies are also available for strict carb counting. Keto dieters should prioritize sodium (3,000-5,000mg daily) and potassium (3,500-4,700mg daily) from food and supplements combined.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can I take too many electrolytes?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes. Excessive sodium intake can elevate blood pressure. Excessive potassium (hyperkalemia) can cause dangerous heart rhythm disturbances. Excessive magnesium (hypermagnesemia) can cause diarrhea and, in extreme cases, cardiac arrest. However, for healthy adults with normal kidney function, the amounts in electrolyte gummies (100-500mg sodium, 99mg potassium per serving) are well within safe limits even with multiple servings per day. People with kidney disease, heart failure, or those taking potassium-sparing diuretics should consult their physician before supplementing.' },
    },
