    <h2 id="why-electrolytes">Why Electrolytes Matter for Hydration and Performance</h2>

    <p>Electrolytes are minerals that carry electrical charges in solution, enabling the fundamental biological processes that keep you alive and performing: nerve impulse transmission, muscle contraction, heartbeat regulation, fluid balance across cell membranes, and pH homeostasis. The four primary electrolytes lost through sweat — sodium, potassium, magnesium, and chloride — must be replenished to maintain these functions during and after physical activity.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">75%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of Americans are chronically dehydrated according to a 2023 survey by the National Institutes of Health. <strong>Even a 2% reduction in body water can impair athletic performance by 10-20%</strong>, reduce cognitive function, and trigger early fatigue during exercise.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The electrolyte gummy format solves a practical problem that powder packets and sports drinks cannot: portability without water. Runners can carry a few gummies in a pocket. Hikers can stash them in a pack. Travelers can maintain electrolyte balance without mixing drinks. The trade-off is that gummies must be consumed with water separately — they do not provide fluid hydration on their own. When paired with adequate water intake, electrolyte gummies deliver the same mineral replacement as liquid electrolyte products.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Sodium (Na+)</strong>
        <p>The primary electrolyte lost through sweat (500-1,500mg per liter). Regulates fluid balance, blood volume, and nerve signaling. The most critical electrolyte to replace during exercise. Many electrolyte products are too low in sodium to meaningfully compensate for sweat losses.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Potassium (K+)</strong>
        <p>Essential for muscle contraction, heart rhythm, and cellular fluid balance. Lost at ~100-200mg per liter of sweat. Works in opposition to sodium across cell membranes (sodium-potassium pump). Deficiency causes cramping, weakness, and irregular heartbeat.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Magnesium (Mg2+)</strong>
        <p>Cofactor in 300+ enzymatic reactions including ATP production, muscle relaxation, and nerve function. Lost at ~10-30mg per liter of sweat. Deficiency causes cramps, fatigue, and impaired recovery. The most commonly under-replaced electrolyte in athletes.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Chloride (Cl-)</strong>
        <p>Pairs with sodium in sweat (lost as NaCl). Maintains stomach acid production, fluid balance, and cellular osmolarity. Generally addressed automatically when sodium is adequately replaced, as most sodium sources also contain chloride.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>The American College of Sports Medicine recommends <strong>300-600mg of sodium per hour during exercise lasting longer than 60 minutes</strong>. Most commercial sports drinks contain only 100-200mg sodium per 8oz serving — inadequate for moderate to heavy sweaters. Electrolyte gummies with higher sodium content can bridge this gap more efficiently.</p>
      <cite>American College of Sports Medicine — Exercise and Fluid Replacement Position Stand</cite>
    </div>

