    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Electrolyte Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do electrolyte gummies work as well as drinks?</summary>
      <p>They deliver the same minerals but lack the immediate water that drinks provide. Pair gummies with water for optimal hydration. Gummies are more convenient for running, hiking, and travel. Mineral absorption is comparable when adequate water is consumed alongside.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How many electrolytes do I lose during exercise?</summary>
      <p>Primary loss is sodium: 500-1,500mg per liter of sweat. Potassium: ~100-200mg/L. Magnesium: ~10-30mg/L. A moderate 1-hour workout depletes ~800mg sodium. Endurance athletes in heat can lose 2,000-4,000mg sodium over 2+ hours.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When should I take electrolyte gummies?</summary>
      <p>Before exercise: 30-60 minutes prior. During: every 30-45 minutes for sessions over 60 minutes. After: within 30 minutes post-workout. For daily use: morning or afternoon for general electrolyte needs. Always consume with adequate water.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What are signs of electrolyte imbalance?</summary>
      <p>Early: cramps, fatigue, headache, dark urine. Moderate: nausea, irregular heartbeat, numbness. Severe: confusion, seizures (requires medical attention). Monitor urine color, weigh before/after exercise, and note cramping patterns.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much sodium do I need during exercise?</summary>
      <p>ACSM recommends 300-600mg/hour for exercise over 60 minutes. Heavy sweaters may need 600-1,000mg/hour. Most gummies provide 100-250mg per serving, so 1-3 servings per hour covers most athletes.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are electrolyte gummies keto-friendly?</summary>
      <p>Most contain 2-4g sugar — negligible for keto. Sugar-free options are available. Electrolyte supplementation is especially important on keto, as low insulin increases mineral excretion. Prioritize sodium (3,000-5,000mg/day) and potassium (3,500-4,700mg/day) on keto.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take too many electrolytes?</summary>
      <p>Excessive sodium raises blood pressure. Excessive potassium can cause dangerous arrhythmias. However, amounts in gummies (100-250mg sodium per serving) are safe for healthy adults even with multiple daily servings. People with kidney disease, heart failure, or on certain medications should consult their physician.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are electrolyte gummies better than sports drinks?</summary>
      <p>Different purposes. Sports drinks provide electrolytes + water + carbs simultaneously — ideal during prolonged exercise. Gummies provide concentrated portable minerals without liquid. Gummies typically have less sugar. For best results, take gummies with water to combine mineral replacement with fluid intake.</p>
    </details>

